{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"77e141dd-c612-403d-81bd-a2516941586d","content":"Since MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0 defaults to VSTest when you set `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>`, here's what to change:\n\n### In your `.csproj`:\n\n**Remove** (or set to `false`):\n```xml\n<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n```\n\nThat's the key change. MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 uses **Microsoft.Testing.Platform by default** — `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` was opting you *out* of it. Removing it switches you over.\n\n### Other things to be aware of:\n\n1. **Running tests** — Use `dotnet test` as usual; it works with both runners. You can also run the test project directly (`dotnet run`) with Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\n2. **CLI differences** — Filters now use `--filter` with the same syntax, but some VSTest-specific `.runsettings` options may need updating.\n\n3. **If you use `dotnet test` arguments** like `--logger`, verify they're supported by the new platform. The most common ones (e.g., `trx`, `console`) are supported.\n\n4. **CI pipelines** — If your CI passes VSTest-specific arguments, review them. Microsoft.Testing.Platform supports `--results-directory`, `--filter`, etc.\n\n### TL;DR\n\nJust **delete** `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` from your project file. MSTest.Sdk 3.8.0 already includes everything needed for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"444fe3bd-3acd-4117-a3be-ee2c4fc446b1","outputTokens":377,"requestId":"A02F:1FF93E:C24745:E339C7:69FE86A1"},"id":"10025c18-d870-496b-9d1c-e4fded74054e","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:58:19.076Z","parentId":"cc5159fd-074e-459b-9ca7-ab551863d9ea"}
